avid Walliams","type":"keyword","sectionId":"tv-and-radio","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/david-walliams","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tv-and-radio/david-walliams","sectionName":"Television & radio","references":[]},{"id":"books/childrens-funny-books","webTitle":"Funny books (children and teens)","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-funny-books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/childrens-funny-books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/childrens-user-reviews","webTitle":"Children's user reviews","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/childrens-user-reviews","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/childrens-user-reviews","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-02-10T14:00:39Z","webTitle":"Gold Fame Citrus by Claire Vaye Watkins review – a wild trip in the American west","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"books/2016/feb/10/gold-fame-citrus-by-claire-vaye-watkins-review","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Justine Jordan","headline":"Gold Fame Citrus by Claire Vaye Watkins review – a wild trip in the American west","trailText":"A journey through a near-future California peopled by Mad Max-ish revellers and sun-drunk survivors of climate change","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>In her debut novel, Claire Vaye Watkins continues a journey into the landscape and mythology of the American west that began with her impressive short-story collection <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/nov/07/dylan-thomas-prize-awards-and-prizes\"><em>Battleborn</em></a>. Since gold-rush times, California has been a draw for the restless, the hopeful and the desperate, in search of wealth, Hollywood stardom or just fruit-picking work: gold, fame, citrus. Now, in Vaye Watkins’ near-future setting, desertification caused by climate change has emptied it out again.</p> <p>Luz, a former model still smarting from the abuses of the industry, has turned down a place on a government “evac” to eke out a life with ex-soldier Ray, who is running from the authorities and the “forever war”. We first meet them squatting in the abandoned mansion of an LA starlet, with capable Ray organising the water rations and “shitting hole”, and strung-out Luz playing dress-up with the starlet’s wardrobe and ploughing through biographies of the west’s founding fathers. It takes time to work out just how far along towards the end of the world we are; in the book’s opening chapters Vaye Watkins keeps the reader as disoriented as her parched and sun-drunk characters, but the empty swimming pools and intense light conjure <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/jgballard\">JG Ballard</a>’s environmental dystopias as well as <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/margaretatwood\">Margaret Atwood</a>’s.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/jan/31/claire-vaye-watkins-gold-fame-citrus\">Claire Vaye Watkins: ‘How come nobody’s ever having sex in the apocalypse?’</a> </p> </aside>  <p>With the majority of the population fled east in search of moister climes, what’s left is the hardcore of the California counterculture. “A little agony was just what this place needed,” reckons Ray’s friend Lonnie, who is stockpiling supplies to build his own small fiefdom. “Reintroduce hardship into the regional narrative. Sift out the posers and moneymen, the tourists, the sunbathers, the whores. Slough off the bourgeoisie! Euthanise the comfort culture! … Luz had heard it all before.” But Luz and Ray know they can’t survive as they are – especially once they have a small child to look after, the odd and possibly damaged Ig, whom they kidnap or rescue from an unsavoury gang at a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/mad-max-fury-road\">Mad Max</a>-ish bacchanalian gathering.</p> <p>So they decide to strike out not for civilisation, which would mean being separated and billeted into labour camps, but deeper into the heart of the deadly, magical west, towards a vast sand dune sea known as the Amargosa after one of the mountain ranges it has swallowed. There are rumours of an impossible town clinging to its fringes, run by a “prophet” who dowses for water. “Very spiritual place,” the two are assured. “Very primal.”</p> <p>Their journey, and what awaits them there, is both nail-biting and digressive, at times lushly overwritten, at times wryly incisive, but always powerful. There are sections told in chorus or set out as a play for voices, freezing the action at dramatic moments; quasi-documentary reportage as well as a fantastical primer to the “neo-fauna” of the dune sea: Mojave ghost crab, jelly scorpion, ouroboros rattlesnake. The whole is crammed with ideas that don’t entirely cohere; but one of the best things about the book is the way Vaye Watkins harnesses the real-life weirdness of the west to intense, hallucinatory effect. Abandoned talc mines in the Mojave desert become an underground prison town where thousands hide from the unforgiving sun; warning signs for future civilisations that were <a href=\"http://www.damninteresting.com/this-place-is-not-a-place-of-honor/\">developed by the US government for the Yucca Mountain nuclear waste repository</a> are woven into a chapter written in the voice of irradiated locals. “This message is a warning about danger … This place is best shunned and left uninhabited … Sending this message was important to us. We considered ourselves to be a powerful culture.”</p> <p>Self-appointed prophets have been announcing the end of the world since records began. “There was always some saviour out in the wilderness,” sighs Luz. But what happens when the end times actually arrive? Vaye Watkins’ portrait of Levi, the leader of the sand dune colony, is a tour de force: chilling, beguiling, paranoid, convincing and pathetic by turns. Her father, Paul Watkins, was a member of the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/us-news/charles-manson\">Charles Manson</a> “Family”, and a haunted family history permeates <em>Gold Fame Citrus</em> as it did <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/battleborn.html\"><em>Battleborn</em></a>, most obviously in the thread around motherhood, loss and the toddler Ig. “I believe every successful piece of art contains some pieces of its creator,” <a href=\"http://www.bucknell.edu/communications/bucknell-magazine/recent-issues/winter-2013/all-this-really-happened.html\">Vaye Watkins has said</a>. “We use our own lives to get at the story that cuts close to the bone.”</p> <p>Her novel certainly cuts deep, perhaps not in the end so much in its character portraits as in its vision of overwhelming natural power: the blinding heat of the sun, that saturates the book with light; the rock and dust of the endless desert. And most of all in her extraordinary creation of the dune sea rising above the earth, ever-growing, ever-moving, unmappable, unknowable, burying everything in its path. Too vast for human comprehension, yet at the same time a tabula rasa for each fragile individual’s desires, it’s a classic example of the Romantic sublime, as mesmerising as it is deadly.</p> <p>• <em>Gold Fame Citrus </em>by Claire Vaye Watkins (Quercus Publishing, £16.99). To order a copy for £12.99, go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/371365/?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only. Phone orders min. p&amp;p of £1.99.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4gema","wordcount":"872","th