eview","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"childrens-books-site/2016/feb/10/mind-your-head-juno-dawson-review","fields":{"commentable":"false","byline":"confessionsofabooklover","headline":"Mind Your Head by Juno Dawson – review","trailText":"<strong>confessionsofabooklover: </strong>‘A survival guide to mental illness’","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>Blue Monday may have been and gone for this year, and even though it was created by a travel agency it does shine light on mental illness, something that we all know is common but aren’t too willing to accept the fact either. Either you have a mental illness or you know someone that has a mental illness. Remember: 1 in 4 people in the UK has a mental health condition each year. Mental illness isn’t some mythical beast, so when I heard Juno Dawson was releasing this book, I was pretty much ready to shove my money in front of a bookseller immediately.</p> <p>Mind Your Head is what I call a survival guide to mental illness. Alongside Dr. Olivia Hewett’s advice, Juno has compiled a guide to mental illnesses; covering everything from anorexia to anxiety in a less serious tone. We all have mental health, so surely we need to start looking after it?</p> <p>Mind Your Head is a book for two kinds of people in relation to mental health: those who can understand and those who can’t.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"679a363276f663e54447bbff69a166047f4626fc\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/679a363276f663e54447bbff69a166047f4626fc/0_0_260_400/260.jpg\" alt=\"Mind Your Head\" width=\"260\" height=\"400\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"></span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>For those who can understand mental health, this book will reaffirm what you already know and teach you what you don’t. You’ll find out about the various other mental health disorders which exist, and learn how to cope with or help others who may have these disorders. For example, I completely understand mental health but had never heard of OSFED (Other Specified Feeding or Eating Disorder) before reading this book. Turns out, it’s the diagnosis given to someone who needs treatment for an eating disorder but who is still within a healthy weight boundary.</p> <p>And for those who can’t understand, this book will make you join the other group, the group which I think you need to be part of. Mind Your Head approaches mental health in a lighthearted yet still serious way, and deals with it through an approach that seems to be subliminally telling you at all times, <em>It’s OK</em>.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">How do I get involved in the Guardian children's books site?</a> </p> </aside>  <p>I really enjoyed this book and think it should be on everyone’s to–buy list. We need to start breeding understanding of mental health in modern day society, and if this book can help us do that, then we should definitely take the time to read it.</p> <ul> <li><strong>Buy this book at the <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/368025/\">Guardian Bookshop</a></strong></li> </ul> <h2><strong>Want to tell the world about a book you’ve read? <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">Join the site</a> and send us your review!</strong></h2>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4g839","wordcount":"414","standfirst":"<p>‘A survival guide to mental illness’</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/feb/10/mind-your-head-juno-dawson-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/2016/feb/10/mind-your-head-juno-dawson-review","s