 revives 1980s coding books for children","trailText":"From Machine Code For Beginners to Computer Spacegames, the books that taught a generation of children to program have returned for free","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>A generation of children in the 1980s learned about programming from a series of computing books by Usborne Publishing. Now the company has rereleased them in free digital versions.</p> <p>Originally aimed at children learning to program their ZX Spectrum, BBC Micro and Commodore 64 computers, the series included books like Practical Things To Do With a Microcomputer, Machine Code for Beginners, and Write Your Own Adventure Programs.</p> <p>Fifteen of the books have been digitised and <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.usborne.com/catalogue/feature-page/computer-and-coding-books.aspx\">made available for download as PDF files</a> from Usborne’s website, with visitors encouraged to download them for personal or educational use, although the books cannot be hosted elsewhere.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"d7c5aa7ea845b490d4fa75e540e202ac18f5ad56\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/d7c5aa7ea845b490d4fa75e540e202ac18f5ad56/0_0_1590_1123/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Computer Spacegames is one of the republished books.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"706\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Computer Spacegames is one of the republished books.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>The digital books are likely to provoke pangs of nostalgia for anyone who grew up with them, although for modern-day children more used to playing games on a console or tablet than writing them on a computer, they are more likely to be historical curiosities.</p> <p>For those in any doubt, Usborne also cautions: “The programs will not run on modern computers.”</p> <p>Many professional games developers got their first experience of programming through these books. Their re-release comes at a time when there is a renewed push to teach programming in schools to children as young as five years old.</p> <p>Usborne has recently published two new books in the series: Lift-the-Flap Computers and Coding, and Coding for Beginners using Scratch. The latter focuses on the <a href=\"https://scratch.mit.edu/\">Scratch</a> programming tool developed at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT), which is used in schools worldwide.</p> <p>“I would say we use more methods to entice children into the information now. But I don’t think the basic level of what they’re interested in and what they understand has changed,” Usborne’s head of digital Lisa Watts <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/oct/01/usborne-books-teach-children-code-lisa-watts\">told the Guardian in 2015</a>.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"d5e9c8884d27811d8da7412883c504efeac01d72\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/d5e9c8884d27811d8da7412883c504efeac01d72/0_0_1600_1134/1000.jpg\" alt=\"A spread from Usborne’s Guide to Programming Tricks &amp; Skills.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"709\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">A spread from Usborne’s Guide to Programming Tricks &amp; Skills.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>In 2016, children are also increasingly able to learn programming skills through tablet apps like <a href=\"https://www.tynker.com/\">Tynker</a>, <a href=\"https://www.gethopscotch.com/\">Hopscotch</a>, <a href=\"http://www.kuatostudios.com/games/hakitzu-elite/\">Coding Warriors</a>, <a href=\"https://www.kodable.com/\">Kodable</a> and <a href=\"http://www.codarica.com/\">Coda Game</a>, which are made available through Google and Apple’s app stores, as well as through partnerships with schools.</p> <p>Many of these apps have slick interfaces where children drag and drop blocks of code. For those kids, the Usborne books will give a sense of a time when typing in a line like LET M$(1)=”SULFACIDOR” was the pathway to making your next game.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4ghy7","wordcount":"378","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/15aa94685d999d1ef0d34368471bc1191850a587/282_265_2450_1470/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-02-13T10:45:00Z","standfirst":"<p>From Machine Code For Beginners to Computer Spacegames, the books that taught a generation of children to program have returned for free</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/feb/10/programming-usborne-1980s-coding-books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/technology/2016/feb/10/programming-usborne-1980s-coding-books","sectionName":"Technology","elements":[{"id":"15aa94685d999d1ef0d34368471bc1191850a587","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/15aa94685d999d1ef0d34368471bc1191850a587/282_265_2450_1470/2000.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/15aa94685d999d1ef0d34368471bc1191850a587","altText":"Usborne’s classic programming books are now available as free PDF files.","caption":"Usborne’s classic programming books are now available as free PDF files.","source":"PR","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"15aa94685d999d1ef0d34368471bc1191850a587","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/15aa94685d999d1ef0d34368471bc1191850a587/282_265_2450_1470/2000.jpg","width":"2000","height":"1200"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/15aa94685d999d1ef0d34368471bc1191850a587/282_265_2450_1470/1000.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/15aa94685d999d1ef0d34368471bc1191850a587","altText":"Usborne’s classic programming books are now available as free PDF files.","caption":"Usborne’s classic programming books are now available as free PDF files.","source":"PR","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"15aa94685d999d1ef0d34368471bc1191850a587","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","s