ianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"world/americas","webTitle":"Americas","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/americas","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/americas","sectionName":"World news","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/news","webTitle":"News","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/news","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/news","references":[]},{"id":"profile/sibyllabrodzinsky","webTitle":"Sibylla Brodzinsky","rcsId":"GNL516401","r2ContributorId":"16445","firstName":"","lastName":"brodzinsky","type":"contributor","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/sibyllabrodzinsky","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/sibyllabrodzinsky","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-02-10T09:29:22Z","webTitle":"The Button Box by Lynn Knight review – do you have a happy relationship with your clothes?","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"false"},"id":"books/2016/feb/10/the-button-box-lifting-the-lid-on-womens-lives-lynn-knight-review","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Claire Harman","headline":"The Button Box by Lynn Knight review – do you have a happy relationship with your clothes?","trailText":"This is a lively and personal history of clothing and the changes in women’s lives, from the white blouse revolution and ‘lazy tongs’ to mini-skirts and the Sindy doll","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>What can a tin of old buttons tell us about anything? Most households have one, lurking at the back of a drawer or the bottom of a sewing basket, and most children have rooted around in it, choosing favourites among the contents or playing with them as tokens. To the memoirist and historian Lynn Knight they are tokens of a different kind, recalling the old clothes they were made to fasten and embellish, the housewives and mothers who made and wore those clothes, and the lives they contained.</p> <p>Inspired by her own shimmering box of toggles, clasps and buckles, Knight takes us on an ingenious tour of domestic and social history over the last century or so: a 1914 thimble makes her think of the “munitionettes” of the Great War, a Land Army button of the second world war, a jet button prompts thoughts of mourning, a suspender clasp of sex, the pearl buttons from a baby’s dress of her mother’s adoption in the 1930s and of other foundling histories. It is to do with class as much as gender, for this writer anyway: her collection comes from a great-grandmother who ran a corner shop in working-class Chesterfield at the turn of the 20th century; a great-aunt who was a low-budget snazzy dresser; and a mother who craved a bit of glamour in the postwar provinces. From this core of very personal material, Knight writes more generally of ordinary women’s lives and changing prospects over three generations, of clothes as self-expression, as defiance, as entertainment, as evidence of frugality and frivolity all rolled into one.</p> <p>We follow her through drab years of shifts, smocks and aprons for poor housewives, to the “white-blouse revolution” of clerical workers in the late 19th century, the service uniforms and “good little suit” of wartime, then on to Hollywood-inspired sequin dreams – history told through haberdashery. Knight trims her story with wonderful bits of arcane clothes-related information: who’d have known that “lazy tongs” were a necessary accessory for the Edwardian straight-fronted corset, enabling the wearer to pick up items they couldn’t bend to reach; or that some employers in the 1960s issued their mini-skirted underlings with “modesty boards” (placed across the lap) to prevent male colleagues from getting too distracted? And who knew that most corsets and trousseau items used to be made by nuns, or that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/oct/20/stevenmorris\">Amy Johnson</a> was dressed by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/jan/24/elsa-schiaparelli-biography-meryle-secrest-review-lobsters-fizz-fashion\">Schiaparelli</a> on her record-breaking 1936 flight to Cape Town? Sewing may never have been much of an aphrodisiac (the Other Woman never knits), but apparently it had contraceptive value, providing a common stalling tactic among working-class wives: “I’ll be up when I’ve just finished darning these thousand socks”.</p> <p>Then there are all the things one knew but had forgotten, such as the fact that bathing suits were commonly home-knitted and hairy, that elastic was made to snap and stockings droop, that within living memory drapers, not chemists, were the purveyors of sanitary towels (discretely disguised in brown paper) and that the minimum order for personalised name tapes was always about 10 times too many. “All over the country”, Knight remarks wryly, “a lifetime’s name tapes exist in buff-coloured packets pushed to the backs of drawers.”</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"7bf4edcf62425239bd7ab92f4b690ed8f0f70dd0\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/7bf4edcf62425239bd7ab92f4b690ed8f0f70dd0/0_0_2816_1912/1000.jpg\" alt=\"A woman in a mini-skirt attracts male attention on Carnaby Street, London, in the 1960s.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"679\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Carnaby Street, London, in the 1960s.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: David Graves/Rex Features</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Knight doesn’t have to look very far back to the days when domestic needlework was required of all girls and women on a daily basis, regardless of whether they were any good at it, when sheets and shirts were mostly made at home and the default position for a female was to have a needle in her hand, especially in hours of leisure. As more women got jobs outside the home, the market for ready-made clothes boomed, though Knight tells us that mass-produced clothes were initially thought of as a shoddy stopgap. They were disapproved of on moral grounds too: women who were liberated from the drudgery of domestic sewing had dangerously “increased opportunity for idleness”.</p> <p>Conditions in the sweatshops producing these garments for working women were famously awful. When the social reformer <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/feb/19/beatrice-webb-tribute\">Beatrice Webb</a> went undercover to investigate them in 1887 she saw for herself how almost impossibly hard the women worked, how it was not enough to be skilful, one had to be unflaggingly efficient in order to earn a pittance. Even so, Knight reports that many seamstresses preferred their lives to being in service; bowed over a machine all day, or finishing buttonholes in inadequate light, at least your thoughts were your own.</p> <p>The colourful box of buttons can often be a reminder of lives constrained and reduced, of women being stitched up by “stitchery”, as <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/jun/17/diaries-little-grey-rabbit-uttley\">Alison Uttley</a> (the children’s writer who had trained as a physicist) disparagingly called it. Was the New Look in the 50s, with its shockingly extravagant yardage of cloth, a fabulous emancipation after the stringencies of wartime rationing, or was it profoundly retrograde, an example of irrational waste that offered the spectacle of young women as “caged birds”? Knight doesn’t seem quite decided on the issue, unlike the ladies of her home town in 1948, as reported by a wonderful headline in the Derbyshire Times: “The ‘New Look’: Chesterfield Women ‘Just Not Interested’”.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--supporting\" data-media-id=\"2b809e1aa934c6489638f30f096bb729a7e73f2f\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/2b809e1aa934c6489638f30f096bb729a7e73f2f/0_0_4200_4164/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Shoppers in the Biba store on Kensington high street, London,  in 1967\" width=\"1000\" height=\"991\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Shoppers in the Biba store on Kensington high street, London, in 1967.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Pictorial Press/Alamy</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>“Fashions come and go but women’s memories endure of the clothes they have loved, longed for and been denied,” Knight says. I tend to remember sartorial disasters better than triumphs, but perhaps there were just more of them. Knight has clearly had a very happy relationship with clothes all her life, and loves to think and talk about their look and feel. She says that many women remember what they paid for a rite-of-passage outfit, and she herself remembers all her best items of teen finery, down to the last choker and pair of crushed-velvet flares. She inspected her <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2012/jul/02/sindy-doll-50th-birthday-relaunch-pedigree-toys\">Sindy</a>’s wardrobe with an already professional eye, it seems, and evokes it so passionately you can almost smell the pungent plastic limbs of “the doll you love to dress”. There is a particular sort of enjoyment in having someone trigger these material memories so deftly; Knight’s paean to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/211768\">Biba</a> will rekindle in many a middle-aged heart happy memories of the bilberry-tinted emporium, just as her evocation of popular 50s cotton prints, with their Eiffel Towers, poodles and pagodas will stir up pictures of forgotten summer frocks, peg bags and aprons. This sort of history-telling, associative and personal, can often slide towards sentimentality; fortunately, Knight is a lively minded writer who is never mawkish about her own past; for her it is full of things she knows she has in common with her readers and ardently wishes to share.</p> <p>• To order<strong> </strong><em><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/372452/s/the-button-box//?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\">The Button Box</a></em><strong> </strong>for £12.79 (RRP £15.99) go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/372452/s/the-button-box//?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4gg8f","wordcount":"1137","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/e5f24d8b0a52658da244ff1835f2bcba914602a3/0_109_5075_3046/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-03-25T15:19:00Z","standfirst":"<p>This is a lively and personal history of clothing and the changes in women’s lives, from the white blouse revolution and ‘lazy tongs’ to mini-skirts and the Sindy doll</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/feb/10/the-button-box-lifting-the-lid-on-womens-lives-lynn-knight-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/feb/10/the-button-box-lifting-the-lid-on-womens-lives-lynn-knight-review","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"e5f24d8b0a52658da244ff1835f2bcba914602a3","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/e5f24d8b0a52658da244ff1835f2bcba914602a3/0_0_5141_3432/2000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"THIS COPYRIGHT IMAGE MUST NOT BE USED WITHOUT PERMISSION","picdarUrn":"GD*29940126","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/e5f24d8b0a52658da244ff1835f2bcba914602a3","suppliersReference":"1227236","altText":"Sindy dolls","caption":"As a girl, Hamilton inspected her Sindy doll’s wardrobe with ‘an already professional eye’.","source":"Jeff Blackler/Rex Features","credit":"Photograph: Jeff Blackler/Rex Features","mediaId":"e5f24d8b0a52658da244ff1835f2bcba914602a3